I don't have live post-2024 market data, so treat this as a structural estimate rather than a current trading call.

If by “the AI bubble bursts” you mean a broad, hype-driven valuation reset and funding pullback in AI, not just a normal correction, my single best estimate is **60%**.

Why that high:
- expectations and capex are running ahead of proven monetization;
- AGI timelines are easy to overhype and disappoint;
- model economics may commoditize faster than investors expect;
- transformative technologies often do produce real bubbles even when the tech is genuinely important.

Why not higher:
- AI already has real utility, adoption, and revenue;
- the biggest spenders are cash-rich incumbents, not only fragile startups;
- governments see AI as strategic, which can keep capital flowing longer than fundamentals alone would.

So my bottom line is: **60%**.  
And for a DeepSeek bet specifically, firm-specific execution, geopolitics, and value-capture risk may matter at least as much as the bubble question.

Subjective best estimate: **55%**.

That’s using “burst” to mean a major, sustained AI-specific valuation reset, not just a normal market pullback.

Why I put it above even odds:
- expectations for monetization and AGI-adjacent progress are very high;
- a lot of AI businesses may end up with weaker moats and lower margins than investors expect;
- capital spending is enormous, so disappointment could trigger a sharp repricing;
- over a five-year window, macro, regulatory, geopolitical, or safety shocks are quite plausible.

Why I don’t put it higher:
- unlike classic bubbles, the main AI beneficiaries already have real revenue, cash flow, and strategic importance;
- AI is already useful enough that spending is unlikely to just vanish;
- governments and hyperscalers may keep funding the race even if returns are uneven.

So my single best estimate is **55%**. For a DeepSeek-style frontier-lab bet, the effective risk is probably a bit higher than that, because private frontier valuations are especially sensitive to sentiment.
